# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: age-of-sail-video-game
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] A stand-alone expansion, titled *Age of Sail II: Privateer's Bounty*, was released in 2002.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] The gameplay of *Age of Sail II* features a minimap, helm, and lists of vessels in play.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] The player controls one or more vessels each with a specified number of cannons, health, and sails.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] There are also controls for speed of the gameplay.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] To achieve victory, the player must either cause the enemy ships to surrender, or simply sink them.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] Damage inflicted on a vessel is determined by the type of shots fired (round, chain, grape, canister), and the target (hull/sail).
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] Each fire also inflicts damage on the ship's crew.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] Canister shots are made specifically to inflict damage on crew members.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] The fewer men aboard a ship, the higher chance for the ship to surrender.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] Speed of activities such as manoeuvring the sails, repairing damage, and cannon reload speed are also affected.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] The game was accused by reviewers of the time of having an overcomplicated and sometimes downright broken interface, with unnecessary complication when directing crews to perform the various actions to keep a vessel in operation.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] The 3-D game engine also came in for criticism, occasionally running as slowly as four frames per second in large fleet actions.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-ii] The game received "mixed" reviews according to the review aggregation website Metacritic.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-video-game] The game covered the naval campaigns of the French Revolutionary Wars, Napoleonic Wars and other more minor conflicts in the period 1775 to 1820.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-video-game] In addition to the campaigns there are more than 100 independent scenarios based on significant naval actions including the battles of Trafalgar and Camperdown.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-video-game] The game includes a scenario editor with over 2,000 historically accurate sailing ships allowing the extension of the game by the user.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-video-game] TalonSoft announced *Age of Sail* on July 12, 1996.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-video-game] It was initially scheduled for a fall 1996 release.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-video-game] The game received middling scores from *Computer Games Strategy Plus* and *Computer Gaming World*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-video-game] The former publication's Robert Mayer wrote, "It should appeal greatly to fans of naval warfare, but for those gamers not inspired by stories of Trafalgar and St.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-video-game] Vincent, it might just be a bit too austere." Conversely, it received a positive review from William R.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/age-of-sail-video-game] In 2001, *Age of Sail* was followed by the sequel title *Age of Sail II*, developed by the Russian studio Akella.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/akella] The company is named after a Rudyard Kipling's Jungle Book character, Akela the wolf, and its logo is a wolf.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/akella] During 2012, the company was amid multiple lawsuits totalling ₽200,000,000 (roughly $6,000,000) which, combined with the significant developmental difficulties and commercial failings of *Postal III*, pushed Akella to the verge of bankruptcy.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/akella] As a result, the company, while technically still existing, has effectively ceased operations since 2012.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-britain-1999-video-game] Set in World War II, *Battle of Britain* is a computer wargame that simulates the conflict between Germany and the United Kingdom during the Battle of Britain.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-britain-1999-video-game] The game was Grigsby's first game developed for Microsoft Windows.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-britain-1999-video-game] According to David Chong of *Computer Games Strategy Plus*, critical reactions toward the game were "lukewarm", as it received above-average reviews according to the review aggregation website GameRankings.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-britain-1999-video-game] Reviewing the game for *PC Gamer US*, William R.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-britain-1999-video-game] Trotter concluded, "There's a lot to admire in the depth and accuracy of this simulation, but you'd better be a serious student of the World War Two air war.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-britain-1999-video-game] In late 1999, the game received a "follow-up" game from TalonSoft, entitled *12 O'Clock High: Bombing the Reich*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-britain-1999-video-game] It was again designed by Gary Grigsby and Keith Brors.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-britain-1999-video-game] It reused the game engine from *Battle of Britain*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-britain-1999-video-game] In 2009, publisher Matrix Games reworked and re-released the game and *12 O'Clock High* together as *Gary Grigsby's Eagle Day to Bombing the Reich*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The **Battle of Camperdown** (Dutch: *Zeeslag bij Kamperduin*) was fought on 11 October 1797 between the Royal Navy's North Sea Fleet under Admiral Adam Duncan and a Batavian Navy fleet led by Vice-Admiral Jan Willem de Winter.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Duncan's fleet won a complete victory over de Winter's in what was the most significant engagement between British and Batavian forces during the French Revolutionary Wars, capturing eleven ships without losing any of their own.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] In 1795, the Dutch Republic was overrun by France and reorganised into the Batavian Republic, a French sister republic.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] After several French Navy campaigns ended in disaster, the Batavian navy was ordered to move to Brest in 1797.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] This rendezvous never occurred, as the French and their allies failed to capitalise on the Spithead and Nore mutinies that paralysed the British Channel and North Sea fleets in the spring of 1797.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] By September, the Batavian navy was blockaded in the Texel by the North Sea Fleet under Duncan, though the British were forced to return to Yarmouth for supplies in October.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] De Winter used the opportunity to lead the Batavian fleet into the North Sea; when they returned to the Dutch coast on 11 October, a waiting Duncan intercepted them off Camperduin.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Attacking the Batavian line of battle in two groups, Duncan's ships broke through its rear and van before engaging with de Winter's frigates.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The battle split into a leeward melee, where superior British forces overwhelmed the Batavian rear, and a windward melee, where a more even exchange centred on battling flagships.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] As the Batavians attempted to reach shallower waters and escape Duncan's attack, the British leeward ships joined the windward melee and forced de Winter's flagship *Vrijheid* and ten other ships to strike their colours.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The loss of *Vrijheid* prompted the remaining Batavian ships to disperse and retreat, and Duncan ordered his fleet to sail back to Yarmouth with their prizes.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Struck by gales *en route*, two prizes were wrecked and another had to be recaptured before Duncan's fleet reached England.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Casualties in both fleets were heavy, and the Batavian Navy was broken as an independent fighting force, losing eleven ships and more than 1,100 men.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] In the winter of 1794–1795, forces of the French Republic overran the neighbouring Dutch Republic during the French Revolutionary Wars.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The French then reorganised the country as a client state named the Batavian Republic, and it joined France against the allies in the War of the First Coalition.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] One of the most important Dutch assets of which the French gained control was the Dutch States Navy.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The Dutch fleet provided a substantial reinforcement to the French forces in northern European waters, which were principally based at Brest on the Atlantic Ocean and whose main opponent was the Royal Navy's Channel Fleet.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The location of the main anchorage of the Dutch fleet in the waters off the Texel prompted a reorganisation of the distribution of British warships in Northern European waters, with a new focus on the importance of the North Sea.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] With the Navy suffering severe shortages in men and equipment and with other theatres of war deemed more important, small, old and poorly maintained ships were activated from reserve and based in harbours in East Anglia, principally the port of Yarmouth, under the command of Admiral Adam Duncan.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The 65-year-old Duncan was a veteran of the wars of the War of the Austrian Succession (1740–1748), the Seven Years' War (1756–1763) and the American Revolutionary War (1775–1783) and had fought at numerous engagements with distinction and success.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Standing at 6 ft 4 in (1.93 m) he was also noted for his physical strength and size: a contemporary described him as "almost gigantic".
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The French Navy had suffered a series of one-sided defeats in the opening years of the war, suffering heavy losses at the Glorious First of June in 1794 and during the *Croisière du Grand Hiver* the following January.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] In late 1796, after prompting from representatives of the United Irishmen (a society dedicated to ending British rule of the Kingdom of Ireland), the French Atlantic Fleet launched a large scale attempt to invade Ireland, known as the *Expédition d'Irlande*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] This too ended in disaster, with twelve ships lost and thousands of men drowned in fierce winter gales.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Their ambitions frustrated, the representatives of the United Irishmen, led by Wolfe Tone, turned to the new Batavian state for support and were promised assistance in the coming year by a united French and Dutch fleet.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] A plan was formulated to merge the French and Dutch fleets and attack Ireland together in the summer of 1797.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] For the Royal Navy, the early years of the war had been successful, but the commitment to a global conflict was creating a severe strain on available equipment, men and financial resources.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Wages had not been increased since 1653, and were usually months late, rations were terrible, shore leave forbidden, and discipline harsh.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Tensions in the fleet had been gradually rising since the start of the war, and in February 1797, anonymous sailors from the Channel Fleet at Spithead sent letters to their former commander, Lord Howe, soliciting his support in improving their conditions.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] For a month the fleet remained at stalemate, until Lord Howe was able to negotiate a series of improvements in conditions that induced the strikers to return to regular service.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The mutiny had achieved almost all of its aims; increasing pay, removing unpopular officers, and improving conditions for the men serving in the Channel Fleet and, ultimately, the whole navy.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] While the upheaval continued at Spithead, Duncan had retained order in the North Sea Fleet at Yarmouth by the sheer force of his personality.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] When men from his flagship, HMS *Venerable*, clambered up into the rigging and roared three cheers in a prearranged signal for the revolt to begin on 1 May, Duncan initially threatened to run the ringleader through with his sword.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Calmed by his subordinates, he instead assembled his officers and the Royal Marines aboard his ship and advanced on the men in the rigging, demanding to know what they were doing.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] So fierce was his tone that the men fell silent and hesitantly returned to their quarters except for five ringleaders, whom he admonished personally on his quarterdeck before issuing a general pardon and dismissing them to their duty.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] A week later, when a similar outbreak of mutiny affected the fourth rate ship, HMS *Adamant*, under Captain William Hotham, Duncan again acted decisively, coming aboard *Adamant* as the crew rebelled and demanding to know if there was any man who disputed his authority.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] When a sailor stepped forward, Duncan seized him by his shirt and dangled him over the side of the ship with one arm crying, "My lads – look at this fellow – he who dares to deprive me of command of the fleet".
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Despite his initial success, Duncan was unable to retain control in the face of a more widespread revolt on 15 May among the ships based at the Nore, which became known as the Nore Mutiny.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Led by a sailor named Richard Parker, the Nore mutineers quickly organised and became a significant threat to water traffic in the Thames Estuary.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Duncan was informed that his fleet at Yarmouth might be ordered to attack the mutineers and, although reluctant, responded, "I do not shrink from the business if it cannot otherwise be got the better of".
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] When rumours of the plan reached the fleet at Yarmouth, the crew of *Venerable* also expressed their distaste with the plan, but reaffirmed their promise of loyalty to their admiral whatever the circumstances.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] News then arrived that the Dutch fleet under De Winter was preparing to sail, and Duncan's fleet was ordered by Lord Spencer to blockade the Dutch coast.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Duncan issued orders for the fleet to weigh anchor, but the men disobeyed and ship after ship overthrew their officers and joined the mutineers at the Nore.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Eventually Duncan was left with only his own *Venerable* and Hotham's *Adamant* to contain the entire Dutch fleet.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] He was subsequently joined by two additional ships, HMS *Russell* and *Sans Pareil*, and on the fourth day, with conditions still perfect for the Dutch, he anchored his squadron in the Marsdiep Channel and gave orders for them to fight until their ships sank, thereby blocking the channel.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] In a speech to his men, he announced that "The soundings are such that my flag will continue to fly above the water after the ship and her company have disappeared".
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The expected attack never came: the Dutch army that was to have joined the fleet was not prepared, and Duncan's misleading signals had successfully convinced De Winter that a large British fleet waited just beyond the horizon.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The winds subsequently changed direction, and, on 10 June, six more ships joined Duncan's squadron from the Channel Fleet, and, on 13 June, a Russian squadron arrived.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] While Duncan had been at sea, the Nore Mutiny had acrimoniously fallen apart under blockade by government forces.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Cut off from food supplies and with public support decidedly against the mutiny, Parker issued threats that the ships under his control would be handed over to the French government.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Fighting subsequently broke out between the radical leaders and the moderate majority of seamen, and the ships gradually deserted Parker and returned to their anchorages, so that by 12 June only two ships still flew the red flag of the mutineers.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Eventually, the last rebellious ship, Parker's own HMS *Sandwich*, surrendered on 14 June.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] By the middle of August 1797, after six weeks of constant easterly winds that kept his ships trapped in their harbour, De Winter decided that an attempt to join the French at Brest as the first stage of an invasion of Ireland was impractical and he abandoned the plan.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] In part this decision was due to the strength of Duncan's reconstituted fleet, which had increased to 17 ships of the line with the addition of the vessels returned from the Nore.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Duncan's men were also better trained and more experienced than their Dutch counterparts, having spent considerably longer at sea and having been taught to fire three rounds a minute to the Dutch two.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] In addition to his concerns about the proficiency of his men, De Winter was also worried about their loyalty: the dominion of France over the Batavian Republic and the country's enforced participation in distant theatres of warfare were unpopular among the Dutch people.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Although De Winter was an avowed republican, who had fought in the French Army against the Netherlands between 1793 and 1795, support for the House of Orange remained strong among the Dutch population and with the fleet's sailors.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Their arrival off Texel on 6 October coincided with De Winter's much delayed expedition.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] He may also have been hoping to resurrect the plan to augment the French at Brest if he was able to pass westwards down the English Channel undetected.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Within hours, Trollope had discovered and followed De Winter.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The Dutch fleet was watched constantly by the ships Duncan had sent to observe them, and when Dutch preparations to sail were observed, a message was sent back to Duncan informing him of the Dutch movements.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The squadron under my command are unmoored and I shall put to sea immediately." Before midday, Duncan had sailed with the 11 ships that were ready and steered for the mouth of the Texel, intending to intercept De Winter on his return.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] By evening his fleet was at full strength, three stragglers having rejoined, and on the afternoon of 10 October his ships were anchored off the Dutch port, scouts reporting 22 merchant ships in the harbour but no sign of De Winter's warships.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Since leaving the Texel, De Winter had been unable to escape from Trollope's ships: on the evening of 10 October, several Dutch vessels were detached to drive his squadron away while the Dutch fleet lay off the Maas, but could not close with the faster British vessels.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Having failed to make the rendezvous off the Maas, De Winter then turned to the northwest, cruising off Lowestoft in Suffolk and again unsuccessfully attempting to drive away Trollope's squadron.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] There, reports from Dutch fishing vessels of Duncan's appearance off the Texel reached De Winter and he immediately recalled his ships and ordered the fleet to turn back towards the Dutch coast, aiming for the village of Scheveningen.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Meanwhile, further messages from Trollope reporting the Dutch movements had reached Duncan and he turned his fleet west, following the Dutch coastline.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] At 07:00 on the morning of 11 October Trollope's squadron sighted sails to the northeast and, after confirming that they were Duncan's fleet, signalled that the Dutch fleet was approximately 3 nautical miles (5.6 km) further to the southwest, becoming visible to the fleet by 08:30.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The first clear sighting was reported by Captain Peter Halkett of *Circe*, who had climbed the mainmast to get a better view.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] At this point, the Dutch were sailing towards land, approximately 9 nautical miles (17 km) off the coast of North Holland, close to the village of Camperduin.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The weather was poor, with heavy seas and strong wind from the southeast broken by frequent rain squalls, but this did not prevent hundreds of Dutch civilians gathering on the dunes to watch the impending combat.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] At 09:00, Duncan made the signal to prepare for battle while De Winter organised his ships into a line of battle to meet the British attack in a solid defensive formation, sailing on the port tack in a northeasterly heading.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] As they manoeuvred into their assigned stations, the Dutch fleet drew closer to the shore.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Duncan intended to follow Lord Howe's manoeuvres at the Glorious First of June three years earlier and bring each ship through the Dutch line between two opponents, but the Dutch formation and proximity to the shore rendered this plan impractical.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] To compensate, Duncan signalled for his ships to form line and sail southeast on the port tack so that they had the wind directly behind them.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] He fired signal guns to alert his captains and then ordered them to "engage the enemy as arriving up" and for his van to attack the Dutch rear.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] At 11:00, Duncan sought to remedy increasing gaps between his vessels by ordering the faster ships to slow down and wait for their compatriots.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] He then made an effort to re-establish the line on the starboard tack before realising that the Dutch fleet was still in order awaiting the British attack and continually drawing closer to the dangerous coastline.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Abandoning his previous signals, Duncan ordered the entire fleet to turn towards the Dutch and attack directly, each ship to "steer for and engage her opponent".
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The combined effect of Duncan's orders was to split his fleet into two uneven divisions, each sailing in a loose formation towards the unified Dutch line.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The northern, or windward, division comprised six third rate ships of the line, two fourth rate ships and the frigate *Circe*, tasked with repeating signals from the flagship *Venerable*, which led the division with HMS *Triumph* and *Ardent* close behind.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] This force was aiming for the Dutch flagship, *Vrijheid*, which lay fifth in the Dutch line.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The southern, or leeward, division comprised eight third rate ships of the line and the repeater frigate HMS *Beaulieu*, and was led by Vice-Admiral Richard Onslow on HMS *Monarch*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Onslow's force was aiming for the rear of the Dutch line, to strike the fourth ship from the end.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Behind the two divisions lay a line of small craft tasked with repeating Duncan's signals so that the entire fleet could see his intentions.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] At 11:53, Duncan raised the signal for each ship to pass through the Dutch line and attack from the far side, but the poor weather prevented the more distant ships from recognising the signal.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] De Winter had originally intended to close his line up into a solid defensive platform and retreat to shallower waters while Duncan formed his own line of battle, but the sudden, disorganised British attack had thrown his plans into confusion.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] As a result, gaps had opened up between his van, centre and rear, leaving the last four ships greatly outnumbered and unsupported.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The Dutch line of battle was accompanied by a second line to the east, formed from ten frigates, brigs and smaller craft.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] These vessels, unlike the smaller ships with the British fleet, were well armed and situated so that their guns covered the gaps between the ships that formed the Dutch line of battle, ready to rake any British vessels that attempted to break through.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] At 12:05, Duncan raised the signal ordering his ships to engage the enemy closely.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] At the same time, the Dutch ship *Jupiter*, under Rear-Admiral Hermanus Reijntjes, fourth from the southern end of the line, opened fire on the rapidly approaching *Monarch*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] As he did, the Dutch frigate *Monnikkendam* and the brig *Daphné* pulled out of the second line and attempted to fill the gap *Monarch* had created, firing into the British ship of the line as they did so.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] In response, Onslow opened fire on the smaller vessels, destroying the frigate's wheel and damaging the rigging, so that the ship fell back, followed later by the severely damaged brig.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] In the confusion, the tail of the Dutch line disintegrated into a chaotic melee, with eight British ships of the line fighting four Dutch and the frigate *Monnikkendam*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] So close was the action that the British ships found themselves at risk of firing into one another in the high seas, heavy rain and poor visibility.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The Dutch centre, consisting of the ships of the line *Brutus*, *Leijden* and the fifth rate razee *Mars*, pulled away from the engagement behind them under Rear-Admiral Johan Bloys van Treslong, coming under only distant fire from the ships of Onslow's division.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Isolated, the Dutch rearguard were rapidly overwhelmed, with *Jupiter*, *Haarlem*, *Alkmaar* and *Delft* all surrendering to Onslow's attack before 13:45, while the battered *Monnikkendam* was seized by the frigate *Beaulieu*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] While the Dutch rearguard was overwhelmed by British numbers, a more equal combat was being contested to the north.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] There the combat was centred around the two flagships, Duncan's *Venerable* engaging De Winter's *Vrijheid* 18 minutes after *Monarch* broke the line to the south.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] While *Venerable* had diverted south, *Vrijheid* had been attacked from the west by *Ardent* under Captain Richard Rundle Burges.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The smaller British ship had soon suffered more than a hundred casualties, including Burges killed, under the combined fire of De Winter's flagship and the next ship ahead, *Admiraal Tjerk Hiddes De Vries*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Only the arrival of *Venerable* alongside *Vrijheid* allowed *Ardent* a brief respite.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] During the fight, Burges' men "fought like maniacs", including the wife of one of the gunners who insisted on joining her husband at his gun, until her legs were torn off by cannon fire.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Within a short period however both *Venerable* and *Ardent* were surrounded, as at least one of the frigates from the second line joined the attack on the two isolated British vessels.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] At the height of the combat, the colours and signal flags on *Venerable* were brought down by cannon fire.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] To ensure that there was no suggestion that the flagship had surrendered, a sailor named Jack Crawford scrambled to the top of the mainmast and replaced them as the battle raged beneath him.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] To support Duncan, Captain William Essington of HMS *Triumph* and Captain Sir Thomas Byard of HMS *Bedford* drove forward into the battle, *Triumph* coming close alongside the Dutch *Wassenaar* and opening a heavy fire while *Bedford* attacked *Admiraal Tjerk Hiddes De Vries* and *Hercules*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] At the tip of the line, *Beschermer* was attacked by *Belliqueux* to starboard, Captain Inglis passing through the gap between *Beschermer* and *Hercules*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Ahead of this combat, the lead ships HMS *Isis* and *Gelijkheid* fought alongside one another, *Isis* having failed to break through the Dutch line and instead drawn up to port.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The Dutch central division joined the battle at the head of the line shortly after the engagement of *Triumph* and *Bedford*, causing considerable damage to all of the British vessels, particularly *Venerable*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The British flagship was soon isolated in the midst of the Dutch van, engaging *Vrijheid*, *Staaten General*, *Admiral Tjerk Hiddes De Vries* and *Wassenaar* simultaneously.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Despite the heavy odds Duncan continued to fight hard, the British succeeded in knocking out two opponents by wounding Captain Dooitze Eelkes Hinxt of *Beschermer*, which drifted eastwards in confusion, while shots from either *Bedford* or *Triumph* set a powder barrel on *Hercules* on fire.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The blaze on the latter ship, which soon spread to the sails and rigging, prompted a lull in the battle as the crew of *Hercules* desperately attempted to extinguish the blaze and other Dutch ships scrambled to escape the burning vessel as it drifted through the melee.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Shortly afterwards, the battered *Wassenaar* surrendered to *Triumph*, with Captain Holland dead on his quarterdeck.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] *Triumph* then moved on towards the battle between *Vrijheid* and *Venerable*, at which time the crew of *Wassenaar* raised their colours again after being fired on by a Dutch brig.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Following Onslow's victory over the Dutch rearguard, the admiral ordered the least damaged of his ships to sail in support of the outnumbered British ships in the melee at the Dutch van.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] *Powerful* and *Director* were the quickest to respond, joining the attack on *Vrijheid* at 14:00.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] *Russell*, driving northwards to join the attack, encountered the now extinguished *Hercules*, whose crew had thrown all of their ammunition overboard during the fire to prevent the ship exploding.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The ship was thus defenceless, Commander Ruijsoort surrendering immediately.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The remainder of the British fleet now arrived in the battle, Captain John Wells of HMS *Lancaster* firing on the *Beschermer* near the head of the Dutch line.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Aware that their vessel would be unable to resist the attack, *Beschermer*'s surviving officers turned away towards the shore, rapidly followed by the unengaged portions of the Dutch line.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Eventually only the Dutch flagship remained in combat.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] For an hour De Winter continued his resistance, with *Director* holding station off the stern of *Vrijheid* and repeatedly raking it.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] By 15:00, all three masts had been brought down, obstructing the fire of the starboard battery, while De Winter was the only officer who remained uninjured, standing on his wrecked quarterdeck and still refusing to lower his colours.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] In an attempt to settle the combat, Captain William Bligh of *Director* closed to within 20 yards (18 m) of the Dutch flagship and demanded to know if De Winter surrendered.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The Dutch admiral replied "What do you think about it?", and then attempted to personally raise signals demanding reinforcements from the rest of his fleet, only to find that the halyards had been shot away.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] De Winter then summoned the ship's carpenter and ordered him to repair his barge, so that the admiral could transfer command to another ship and continue the battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] When British sailors from *Director* boarded the drifting flagship, De Winter was discovered assisting the carpenter with repairs to the barge.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] On being informed that he was a prisoner of war, he replied "This is my destiny not foreseen" and, after checking on a mortally wounded officer who lay on the quarterdeck, he followed the boarding party back to their boat for the trip to *Venerable*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] De Winter was immediately taken to see Duncan, the Dutch officer holding out his sword as a token of surrender.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Duncan refused the weapon, instead shaking De Winter's hand and insisting "I would much rather take a brave man's hand than his sword".
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] In addition to the losses in the rear, five ships of the Dutch van had been captured as well as the frigate *Ambuscade* that had attacked from the second line.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The remainder of the Dutch ships had fled, making rapid progress towards the coastal shallows.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Duncan did not follow them: the Dutch coast between Kamperduin and Egmond was only 5 nautical miles (9.3 km) away, his ship lay in just 9 fathoms (18 yards (16 m)) of water and the weather was too fierce and his ships too battered to risk combat in shoal waters.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Instead he ordered his ships to ensure control of their prizes and to return to Britain.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Casualties in the battle were very heavy on both sides, and historians such as William James have noted that the losses among the British ships were proportionally much higher than when British fleets met French or Spanish opposition.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] This was attributed to the Dutch tactics, mirrored by the British, of firing at the enemy hulls rather than attempting to disable their masts and rigging as in other continental navies.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The worst hit of the British ships were those in the first wave, such as *Ardent* with 148 casualties, *Monarch* with 136 and *Belliqueux* with 103, while both *Adamant* and *Agincourt* escaped without a single man killed or wounded.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Among the dead were Captain Burges of *Ardent* and two lieutenants, while the wounded included Captain Essington of *Triumph* and twelve lieutenants.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] In total, British losses were recorded after the battle as 203 killed and 622 wounded, although later assessments based on charitable requirements of those wounded or killed gave the higher figures of 228 killed and 812 wounded, including 16 of the latter who subsequently died.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Many of the British ships were badly damaged, taking on large quantities of water through damaged hulls.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] One of the worst hit was *Venerable*, which had to be completely dismantled and reconstructed after returning to Britain before the ship was ready for active service again.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Dutch casualty returns, particularly on the captured ships, were vague, and only partially complete.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Among the losses were Captain Hinxt of *Beschermer* and Captain Holland of *Wassenaar*, both of whom were killed early in the battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Also lost were Captain Van Rossum of *Vrijheid*, who was struck in the thigh by a cannonball and died shortly afterwards from the effects of the wound, and Admiral Reijntjes who died while a prisoner in England as a result of the wounds he suffered aboard *Jupiter*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] His remains were subsequently returned to the Netherlands with full military honours.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] On *Venerable*, Duncan assembled all of those men fit to attend for a church service to "return thanks to Almighty God for all His mercies showered on them and him." For the next 24 hours the 66-year-old Duncan remained on duty without a break, organising the scattered fleet on its journey home.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The British admiral did find time however to play a game of whist in his cabin with De Winter after dinner: when the Batavian admiral lost a rubber, he commented that it was hard to be beaten twice in one day by the same man.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] De Winter was permitted to send despatches to the Batavian government, in which he blamed Story and his centre for not maintaining the combat longer.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] He also attributed overwhelming British numbers to his defeat and suggested that he may have captured some of the British fleet if he had been better supported.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] When this letter was later published it provoked a storm of criticism in Britain, one officer describing it as "a garbled account which, for ought I know, might have been collected by people on shore who knew nothing of the action".
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] During the afternoon of 12 October, a gale sprang up which inflicted further damage to the battered ships and caused water to gush through the many shot holes in the ships' hulls.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Aboard the Batavian ships, the situation was especially dangerous.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Two other prizes were lost to the British fleet: *Monnikkendam* had been supplied with a prize crew of 35 men from *Beaulieu*, but had become separated during the gales and lost its remaining masts and spars.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The crew fitted jury masts, but they too collapsed and the hull flooded to a depth of 14 feet (4.3 m).
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] On 12 October, aware that the ship would soon founder, the prize master instructed the Batavian boatswain to run the ship onto the Dutch coast at West Cappel.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Local boats came out to the stranded vessel and all aboard were saved, the 35 British prisoners taken to a prison hulk at Vlissingen.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The ship itself was wrecked beyond repair and abandoned.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The other captured frigate, *Ambuscade*, was also driven ashore in a sinking state and the prize crew made prisoner, but in that case the ship was salvaged and later returned to Batavian service.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] In contrast to the British difficulties, the survivors of the Batavian fleet had few problems returning to the Texel, with the exception of *Brutus*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Admiral Bloys van Treslong had sailed for the coast off Hinder with two brigs, and there on 13 October the 40-gun British frigate HMS *Endymion* under Captain Sir Thomas Williams found him.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] At 16:30, *Endymion* closed with the larger, but damaged, Batavian ship and opened fire, *Brutus* responding with a broadside of its own.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Williams successfully raked his opponent twice, but the complicated tides of the Dutch coast dragged his ship out of range at 17:30 before he could press his attack any further.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] Firing rockets in the hope of attracting attention from any of Duncan's ships, Williams was rewarded at 22:30 by the arrival of *Beaulieu*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] On 14 October the frigates hunted for their opponents, and found the Batavian ships off the Goeree channel at 05:00.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The frigates closed, and Bloys van Treslong withdrew, passing deeper into Dutch waters and reaching safety at Maese by 07:00.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p01] The British frigates, their quarry having escaped, returned to Duncan's struggling fleet.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] On 17 October 1797, Duncan's limping convoy began to arrive at Yarmouth to be greeted with great celebrations.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Several ships were delayed, with three wallowing off Kentish Knock, three more in Hosley Bay and several still at sea due to an adverse northwesterly wind.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] News of the victory had already spread across Britain, and on 20 October Duncan was created Viscount Duncan of Camperdown and Baron Duncan of Lundie.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Admiral Onslow was made a baronet and Captains Henry Trollope and William George Fairfax were knighted.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] King George III insisted on meeting Duncan personally, and on 30 October set out for Sheerness in the royal yacht HMY *Royal Charlotte* before strong winds and waves forced him back to port on 1 November.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Unable to reach Duncan's flagship, the King instead rewarded the fleet as a whole by pardoning 180 men condemned for their role in the Nore Mutiny and held aboard the prison hulk HMS *Eagle* in the River Medway.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Similar pardons were awarded by Rear-Admiral Peter Rainier to mutineers in the East Indies Squadron.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Gold medals were created and presented to the captains and both Houses of Parliament voted their thanks for their victory.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] All first lieutenants were promoted to commander and Duncan and Onslow were presented with valuable presentation swords valued at 200 and 100 guineas each respectively.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Five decades later the battle was among the actions recognised by a clasp attached to the Naval General Service Medal, awarded upon application to all British participants still living in 1847.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Not all of the reactions were positive: several of Duncan's captains were criticised for their failure to rapidly and decisively engage the enemy, including Captain Wells of *Lancaster*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] The worst criticism fell on Captain John Williamson of *Agincourt*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] *Agincourt* had been barely engaged in the battle and had suffered not one single casualty.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] As a result, Williamson was accused of failing to do his duty by Captain Hopper of *Agincourt*'s Royal Marines and court-martialled on 4 December 1797, at Sheerness aboard *Circe*, on the charges of "disobedience to signals and not going into action" and "cowardice and disaffection".
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Williamson had a history of indecisiveness: in 1779, while a junior officer on Captain James Cook's voyage to the Pacific Ocean, Williamson had prevaricated about bringing boats to evacuate Cook from Kealakekua Bay while under attack by Hawaiians.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] As a result, Cook was trapped on the beach and stabbed to death.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] At the conclusion of the trial on 1 January 1798, Williamson was found guilty of the first charge and not guilty of the latter, resulting in demotion to the bottom of the post captains list and prohibition from further naval service.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Williamson was reported to have died in 1799, shortly after his dismissal from the service, but Edward Pelham Brenton later claimed that he had instead gone into hiding under an assumed name and continued to draw his pension for many years.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] In the Batavian Republic, there were also recriminations against those officers who were deemed to have failed in their duty: De Winter's despatch from London after the battle placed much of the blame with six ships that had failed to follow his orders and had withdrawn early from the battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Several officers were brought up on charges, including Admiral Bloys van Treslong who was convicted at court-martial and dismissed the service although later reinstated, and Commander Souter of *Batavier* who was convicted and imprisoned.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Admiral Story was also criticised, particularly by De Winter, and was only permitted to keep his command once he had satisfied the Batavian government that he had had no option but to retreat.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] All of the captured Batavian ships were bought into the Royal Navy, *Gelijkheid*, *Vrijheid*, *Wassenaar*, *Haarlem* and *Alkmaar* under their own names (although in most cases they were anglicised) and *Admiraal Tjerk Hiddes De Vries* as the simpler *Devries*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Two were completely renamed, due to the prior existence of ships with their names in the Royal Navy; *Jupiter* became HMS *Camperdown* and *Hercules* became HMS *Delft*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] None of these ships was ever in sufficient condition for service in open waters: the damage suffered at Camperdown proved too severe for them to be fully repaired.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] In addition, the Batavian warships had lighter hulls and flatter bottoms than ships of other nations as they were designed to operate off the shallow waters of the Dutch coast, and as a result they were of little use to the ocean-going Royal Navy.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] All the prizes were immediately relegated to harbour duty, and none were used for front-line service.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Since this force had played no part in the battle and had been considered a liability rather than a benefit by the British commanders, the claim was rejected, but legal fees and other claims reduced the eventual payment.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Following the award of the first £10,000 instalment, Duncan was given the unique honour of permission to buy shares on the London Stock Exchange at 7⁄8 market price.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Nevertheless, the effects of the action on the wider war were hugely important.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] The destruction of the Batavian fleet at Camperdown was also a serious blow to French ambitions to invade Ireland, and denied their Atlantic fleet of essential reinforcements; it may even have played a part in Napoleon's decision to abandon efforts to directly invade Britain in early 1798.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] In 1799, a large Anglo-Russian expeditionary force landed in the Netherlands supported by a large fleet under Lord Duncan.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Assailed from both sea and land, a Batavian squadron under Story capitulated without a fight: in what became known as the Vlieter incident, the political divisions between the officers and seamen in Story's fleet resulted in a mutiny during which the sailors threw their ammunition overboard.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] In Britain, the public relief at the restoration of the Royal Navy's authority in the aftermath of the spring mutinies was enormous and helped steady the wavering British government in their pursuit of the war by restoring confidence in Britain's naval supremacy in home waters.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Duncan was subsequently indirectly criticised some years after the battle by his colleague Earl St Vincent, who had won the Battle of Cape St.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Vincent over a Spanish fleet nine months before Camperdown.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] In a letter complaining of Clerk's assertion that he had been responsible for all of the major naval victories of the war, St Vincent wrote that Duncan "was a brave officer, little versed in the subtleties of naval tactics, and who would have been quickly embarrassed by them.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] When he saw the enemy, he rushed upon him without thinking of such and such and order of battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] Duncan himself felt that he could have done more, noting that "We were obliged ... to be rather rash in our attack.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] De Winter was released from captivity in 1798 after news reached Britain that his wife had suffered a stroke, and he subsequently became the Batavian ambassador to France, before resuming command of the Batavian navy at the start of the Napoleonic Wars in 1803.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] He was a trusted subordinate of Louis Bonaparte, King of Holland between 1806 and 1810, and was honoured by Napoleon in 1811 before his sudden death in Paris the following year.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] In literature, the battle has played a central role in the 1968 novel *Sea Road to Camperdown* by Showell Styles, and the 1975 novel *The Fireship* by C.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] The battle also inspired composers, such as Daniel Steibelt, whose composition *Britannia: An Allegorical Overture* was created in honour of the victory and Jan Ladislav Dussek, who created a composition entitled *The Naval Battle and Total Defeat of the Dutch by Admiral Duncan* in 1797.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] The Royal Navy has commemorated the battle through the four ships that bore the name HMS *Camperdown* and seven named HMS *Duncan*, which have maintained close links with Duncan's hometown of Dundee.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] In Dundee, the Battle of Camperdown is commemorated at Camperdown House, originally the Dundee seat of the Viscounts Camperdown, which was completed in 1828 and later became a public park and tourist attraction.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] The bicentennial of the battle was celebrated in Dundee in 1997 with the "Glorious Victory" exhibition at the city's McManus Galleries in conjunction with Camperdown House and the National Museum of Scotland.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] The exhibition became a popular tourist attraction and was viewed by more than 50,000 visitors.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-camperdown-p02] On 11 October a memorial service was held to remember the dead and a new statue of Admiral Duncan unveiled in the town.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The **Battle of Trafalgar** was a fleet action which took place on 21 October 1805 between the Royal Navy and a combined fleet of the French and Spanish navies during the War of the Third Coalition.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] As part of Napoleon's planned invasion of the United Kingdom, the French and Spanish navies planned to take control of the English Channel and provide the French invasion army with safe passage to Britain.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The allied fleet, under the command of French Vice-admiral Pierre-Charles Villeneuve, sailed from the port of Cádiz in southern Spain on 18 October 1805.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] It encountered a British fleet under Vice-Admiral of the White Horatio Nelson, 1st Viscount Nelson in the Atlantic Ocean along the southwest coast of Spain off Cape Trafalgar.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson's fleet was outnumbered, having only 27 ships of the line to the 33 of Villeneuve's fleet which included the largest warship in either fleet, the Spanish ship of the line *Santísima Trinidad*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] To address this imbalance, Nelson sailed his fleet directly at the allied battle line's flank in two columns, hoping to break the line into pieces.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Villeneuve had worried that Nelson might attempt this tactic, but for various reasons, failed to prepare for it.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The crews of the French and Spanish ships were also inexperienced and poorly trained.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The British plan worked almost perfectly; Nelson's columns split the Franco-Spanish fleet in three, isolating the rear from Villeneuve's flagship, *Bucentaure*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The allied vanguard sailed ahead while attempting to turn back, leaving the British temporarily superior in number against the remainder of the allied fleet.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] In the battle that followed, 18 allied ships were captured or destroyed, while the British lost none.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The offensive exposed the leading British ships to intense crossfire as they approached the Franco-Spanish lines.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson's own HMS *Victory* led the front column and was almost knocked out of action.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson was shot by a French musketeer during the battle, and died shortly before it ended.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Villeneuve was captured along with his flagship *Bucentaure*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] He later attended Nelson's state funeral while a captive on parole in Britain.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] After the battle, the senior surviving Spanish commander, Admiral Federico Gravina, led part of the surviving Franco-Spanish fleet away from the storm; he died six months later of wounds sustained during the battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson's victory against the odds and death during battle secured his place as a British national hero.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] His signal to the fleet shortly before the battle, "England expects that every man will do his duty", is regularly quoted and paraphrased.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The victory confirmed Britain's naval supremacy and was achieved in part through Nelson's departure from prevailing naval tactical orthodoxy.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Although the battle led to the definitive end of French plans to invade Britain, it had a limited impact on the War of the Third Coalition, which ended a few months later in defeat for Britain and her allies.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The Napoleonic Wars would continue for another decade.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] In 1805, the First French Empire, under Napoleon Bonaparte, was the dominant military land power on the European continent, while the British Royal Navy controlled the seas.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] During the course of the war, the British imposed a naval blockade on France, which affected trade and kept the French from fully mobilising their naval resources.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Despite several successful evasions of the blockade by the French navy, it failed to inflict a major defeat upon the British, who were able to attack French interests at home and abroad with relative ease.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] When the Third Coalition declared war on France, after the short-lived Peace of Amiens, Napoleon renewed his determination to invade Britain.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] To allow his invasion flotilla to reach England, he needed to wrest control of the English Channel from the Royal Navy.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The main French fleets were at Brest in Brittany and at Toulon on the Mediterranean coast.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Other ports on the French Atlantic coast harboured smaller squadrons.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] France and Spain were allied, so the Spanish fleet based in Cádiz and Ferrol was also available.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The British possessed an experienced and well-trained corps of naval officers.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] By contrast, some of the best officers in the French navy had been executed or had left the service during the early part of the French Revolution.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Vice-admiral Pierre-Charles Villeneuve had taken command of the French Mediterranean Squadron following the death of Vice-admiral Louis-René Levassor de Latouche Tréville.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] There had been more competent officers, but they had either been employed elsewhere or had fallen from Napoleon's favour.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Villeneuve had shown a distinct reluctance for facing the Royal Navy after the French defeat at the Battle of the Nile in 1798.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Napoleon's naval plan in 1805 was for the French and Spanish fleets in the Mediterranean and Cádiz to break through the blockade and join forces in the Caribbean.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] They would then return, assist the fleet in Brest to emerge from the blockade, and together clear the English Channel of Royal Navy ships, ensuring a safe passage for the invasion barges.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Early in 1805, Vice-Admiral of the White Horatio Nelson, 1st Viscount Nelson commanded the British fleet blockading the Mediterranean port of Toulon.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson commenced a search of the Mediterranean, supposing that the French intended to make for Egypt, but Villeneuve instead took his fleet through the Strait of Gibraltar, rendezvoused with the Spanish fleet in Cádiz, and sailed as planned for the Caribbean.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Once Nelson realised that the French were crossing the Atlantic, he set off in pursuit.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] He missed them by just days in the West Indies as a result of false information.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Having lured the British to the West Indies, Villeneuve returned from the Caribbean to Europe, intending to break the blockade at Brest.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson, still in fear for Egypt, made to return to the Mediterranean.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The fast sailing corvette taking word of his plans back to the admiralty spotted the French heading further north.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] On receiving this intelligence Lord Barham immediately ordered Admiral Cornwallis to combine his squadron with that of Vice-Admiral Robert Calder off Ferrol and to stretch out thirty to forty leagues into the Atlantic to block the French from entering the Channel.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Calder intercepted the French resulting in an inconclusive engagement during the Battle of Cape Finisterre in which two of the Spanish ships were captured.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Villeneuve abandoned his plan and sailed back to Ferrol in northern Spain.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] There he received orders from Napoleon to return to Brest according to the main plan.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Napoleon's invasion plans for Britain depended on having a sufficiently large number of ships of the line protecting his port of Boulogne on the English Channel.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] This would require Villeneuve's force of 33 ships to join Vice-Admiral Honoré Joseph Antoine Ganteaume's fleet of 21 ships at Brest, along with a squadron of five ships under Captain Allemand, which would have given him a combined force of 59 ships of the line.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] When Villeneuve set sail from Ferrol on 10 August, he was under orders from Napoleon to sail northward toward Brest.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Instead, he worried that the British were observing his manoeuvres, so on 11 August, he sailed southward towards Cádiz on the southwestern coast of Spain.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] With no sign of Villeneuve's fleet, on 25 August, the three French army corps' invasion force near Boulogne broke camp and marched into Germany, where it was later engaged.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] This ended the immediate threat of invasion.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The same month, Admiral Lord Nelson returned home to Britain after two years of duty at sea.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] He remained ashore for 25 days and was warmly received by his countrymen.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Word reached Britain on 2 September about the combined French and Spanish fleet in Cádiz harbour.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson had to wait until 15 September before his ship, HMS *Victory*, was ready to sail.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] On 15 August, Cornwallis decided to detach 20 ships of the line from the fleet guarding the English Channel to sail southward to engage the French and Spanish forces in Spain, leaving the Channel with only 11 ships of the line.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The detached force formed the nucleus of the British fleet at Trafalgar.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] This fleet, under Calder's command, reached Cádiz on 15 September.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson joined the fleet on 28 September to take command.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Hoping to lure the combined Franco-Spanish force out from Cádiz harbour and engage it in a decisive battle, Nelson kept his main force out of sight approximately 50 miles (80 km) offshore and sent a squadron of frigates (faster, but too small for the line of battle) to keep watch on the harbour.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] This was led by Captain Blackwood aboard HMS *Euryalus*, with five frigates, a schooner, and a brig.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson's fleet badly needed provisioning.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] On 2 October, five ships of the line, HMS *Queen*, *Canopus*, *Spencer*, *Zealous*, *Tigre*, and the frigate HMS *Endymion* were dispatched to Gibraltar under Rear-Admiral Sir Thomas Louis for supplies.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] These ships were later diverted for convoy duty in the Mediterranean, although Nelson had expected them to return.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Similarly, HMS *Superb* under Captain Richard Goodwin Keats had been sent to the dockyard for a re-fit after four years at sea, including the chase of Villeneuve, and was expected to return to the fleet where Keats was to be Nelson's second, but the ship was not released in time.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Other British ships continued to arrive, and by 15 October the fleet was up to full strength for the battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson also lost Calder's flagship, the 98-gun *Prince of Wales*, which he sent home as Calder had been recalled by the Admiralty to face a court-martial for his apparent lack of aggression during the engagement off Cape Finisterre on 22 July.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Meanwhile, Villeneuve's fleet in Cádiz was also suffering from a serious supply shortage that could not be easily rectified by the cash-poor French.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The blockade maintained by the British fleet had made it difficult for the Franco-Spanish allies to obtain stores, and their ships were ill-equipped.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Villeneuve's ships were also more than two thousand men short of the force needed to sail.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] These were not the only problems faced by the Franco-Spanish fleet.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The main French ships of the line had been kept in harbour for years by the British blockade with only brief sorties.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The French crews included few experienced sailors, and, as most of the crew had to be taught the elements of seamanship on the few occasions when they got to sea, gunnery was neglected.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The hasty voyage across the Atlantic and back used up vital supplies.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Villeneuve's supply situation began to improve in October, but news of Nelson's arrival made Villeneuve reluctant to leave port.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] His captains had held a vote on the matter and decided to stay in harbour.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] On 21 October, Admiral Nelson had 27 ships of the line with 2148 cannons, and a total of 17000 crewmen and marines under his command.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson's flagship, HMS *Victory*, captained by Thomas Masterman Hardy, was one of three 100-gun first-rates in his fleet.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] He also had four 98-gun second-rates and 20 third-rates.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] One of the third-rates was an 80-gun vessel, and 16 were 74-gun vessels.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The remaining three were 64-gun ships, which were being phased out of the Royal Navy at the time of the battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson also had four frigates of 38 or 36 guns, a 12-gun schooner and a 10-gun cutter.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Against Nelson, Vice-Admiral Villeneuve, sailing on his flagship *Bucentaure*, fielded 33 ships of the line, including some of the largest in the world at the time.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The Spanish contributed four first-rates to the fleet – three of these ships, one at 130 guns (*Santísima Trinidad*) and two at 112 guns (*Príncipe de Asturias*, *Santa Ana*), were much larger than anything under Nelson's command.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The fleet had six 80-gun third-rates (four French and two Spanish), and one Spanish 64-gun third-rate.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The remaining 22 third-rates were 74-gun vessels, of which 14 were French and eight Spanish.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] In total, the Spanish contributed 15 ships of the line and the French 18 along with some 30000 men and marines manning 2632 cannons.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The fleet also included five 40-gun frigates and two 18-gun brigs, all French.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The prevailing tactical orthodoxy at the time involved manoeuvring to approach the enemy fleet in a single line of battle and then engaging broadside in parallel lines.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] In previous times, fleets had usually engaged in a mixed mêlée of chaotic one-on-one battles.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] One reason for the development of the line of battle formation was to facilitate control of the fleet: if all the ships were in line, signalling during battle became possible.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The line also allowed either side to disengage by breaking away in formation; if the opponent chose to continue, their line would be broken as well.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] This often led to inconclusive battles, or allowed the losing side to minimise its losses.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Facing a numerically superior Franco-Spanish line, Nelson wanted to break it into a chaotic mêlée which would force his opponents to fight his well-trained crews ship to ship.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson's solution was to cut the opposing line in three.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Approaching in two columns sailing perpendicular to the Franco-Spanish fleet's line, one towards the centre of the opposing line and one towards the trailing end, his ships would surround the middle third, and force them to fight to the end.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson hoped specifically to cut the line just in front of the French flagship, *Bucentaure*; the isolated ships in front of the break would not be able to see the flagship's signals, which he hoped would take them out of combat while they re-formed.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] This echoed the tactics used by Admiral Duncan at the Battle of Camperdown and Admiral Jervis at the Battle of Cape St.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The main drawback of attacking head-on was that as the leading British ships approached, the Franco-Spanish Combined Fleet would be able to direct raking broadside fire at their bows, to which they would be unable to reply.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] To lessen the time the fleet was exposed to this danger, Nelson had his ships make all available sail (including stunsails), yet another departure from the norm.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] He was also well aware that French and Spanish gunners were ill-trained and would have difficulty firing accurately from a moving gun platform.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The Combined Fleet was sailing across a heavy swell, causing the ships to roll heavily and exacerbate the problem.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson's plan was a carefully calculated gamble.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] During the blockade off the coast of Spain in October, Nelson instructed his captains, over two dinners aboard *Victory*, on his plan for the approaching battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] In an animated conversation with his favourite captain, Richard Goodwin Keats, who was expected to be his second in the forthcoming battle, Nelson explained a refined battle plan whilst the two were walking in the garden of Merton in August 1805.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The order of sailing, in which the fleet was arranged when the opposing fleet was first sighted, was to be the order of the ensuing action so that no time would be wasted in forming two lines.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The first, led by his second-in-command Vice-Admiral Cuthbert Collingwood, was to sail into the rear of the Franco-Spanish line, while the other, led by Nelson, was to sail into the centre and vanguard.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] In preparation for the battle, Nelson ordered the ships of his fleet to be painted in a distinctive yellow and black pattern (later known as the Nelson Chequer) that would make them easy to distinguish from their opponents.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson was careful to point out that something had to be left to chance.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Admiral Villeneuve himself expressed his belief that Nelson would use some sort of unorthodox attack, presciently speculating that Nelson would drive right at his line.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] But his long game of cat and mouse with Nelson had worn him down, and he was suffering from a loss of nerve.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Fearing that his inexperienced officers would be unable to maintain formation in more than one group, he chose to keep the single line that became Nelson's target.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The Combined Fleet of French and Spanish warships anchored in Cádiz under the leadership of Admiral Villeneuve was in disarray.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] On 16 September 1805 Villeneuve received orders from Napoleon to sail the Combined Fleet from Cádiz to Naples.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] At first, Villeneuve was optimistic about returning to the Mediterranean, but soon had second thoughts.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] A war council was held aboard his flagship, *Bucentaure*, on 8 October.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] While some of the French captains wished to obey Napoleon's orders, the Spanish captains and other French officers, including Villeneuve, thought it best to remain in Cádiz.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Villeneuve changed his mind yet again on 18 October 1805, ordering the Combined Fleet to sail immediately even though there were only very light winds.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The sudden change was prompted by a letter Villeneuve had received on 18 October, informing him that Vice-Admiral François Rosily had arrived in Madrid with orders to take command of the Combined Fleet.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Stung by the prospect of being disgraced before the fleet, Villeneuve resolved to go to sea before his successor could reach Cádiz.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] At the same time, he received intelligence that a detachment of six British ships (Admiral Louis' squadron), had docked at Gibraltar, thus weakening the British fleet.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] This was used as the pretext for sudden change.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The weather, however, suddenly turned calm following a week of gales.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] This slowed the progress of the fleet leaving the harbour, giving the British plenty of warning.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Villeneuve had drawn up plans to form a force of four squadrons, each containing both French and Spanish ships.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Following their earlier vote on 8 October to stay put, some captains were reluctant to leave Cádiz, and as a result they failed to follow Villeneuve's orders closely and the fleet straggled out of the harbour in no particular formation.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] It took most of 20 October for Villeneuve to get his fleet organised; it eventually set sail in three columns for the Straits of Gibraltar to the southeast.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] That same evening, *Achille* spotted a force of 18 British ships of the line in pursuit.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The fleet began to prepare for battle and during the night, they were ordered into a single line.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The following day, Nelson's fleet of 27 ships of the line and four frigates was spotted in pursuit from the northwest with the wind behind it.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Villeneuve again ordered his fleet into three columns, but soon changed his mind and restored a single line.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The result was a sprawling, uneven formation.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] At 5:40 a.m. on 21 October, the British were about 21 miles (34 km) to the northwest of Cape Trafalgar, with the Franco-Spanish fleet between the British and the Cape.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] About 6 a.m., Nelson gave the order to prepare for battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] At 8 a.m., the British frigate *Euryalus*, which had been keeping watch on the Combined Fleet overnight, observed the British fleet still "forming the lines" in which it would attack.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] At 8 a.m., Villeneuve ordered the fleet to *wear together* (turn about) and return to Cádiz.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] This reversed the order of the allied line, placing the rear division under Rear-Admiral Pierre Dumanoir le Pelley in the vanguard.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The wind became contrary at this point, often shifting direction.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The very light wind rendered manoeuvring virtually impossible for all but the most expert seamen.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The inexperienced crews had difficulty with the changing conditions, and it took nearly an hour and a half for Villeneuve's order to be completed.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The French and Spanish fleet now formed an uneven, angular crescent, with the slower ships generally to leeward and closer to the shore.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] By 11 a.m., Nelson's entire fleet was visible to Villeneuve, drawn up in two parallel columns.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The two fleets would be within range of each other within an hour.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Villeneuve was concerned at this point about forming up a line, as his ships were unevenly spaced in an irregular formation drawn out nearly 5 miles (8 km) long as Nelson's fleet approached.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] As the British drew closer, they could see that the combined French and Spanish fleet was not sailing in a tight order, but in irregular groups.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson could not immediately make out the French flagship as the French and Spanish were not flying command pennants.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson was outnumbered and outgunned, with the opposing fleet totalling nearly 30000 men and 2568 guns to Nelson's 17000 men and 2148 guns.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The Franco-Spanish fleet also had six more ships of the line, and so could more readily combine their fire.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] There was no way for some of Nelson's ships to avoid being "doubled on" or even "trebled on".
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The battle progressed largely according to Nelson's plan.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] At 11:45, Nelson sent the flag signal, *"England expects that every man will do his duty"*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The term "England" was widely used at the time to refer to the United Kingdom; the British fleet included significant contingents from Ireland, Scotland, and Wales.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Unlike the photographic depiction above, this signal would have been shown on the mizzen mast only and would have required 12 lifts.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] As the battle opened, the French and Spanish were in a ragged curved line headed north.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] As planned, the British fleet was approaching the Franco-Spanish line in two columns.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Leading the northern, windward column in *Victory* was Nelson, while Collingwood in the 100-gun *Royal Sovereign* led the second, leeward, column.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The two British columns approached from the west at nearly a right angle to the allied line.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson led his column into a feint toward the van of the Franco-Spanish fleet and then abruptly turned toward the actual point of attack.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Collingwood altered the course of his column slightly so that the two lines converged at this line of attack.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] At noon, Villeneuve sent the signal "engage the enemy", and *Fougueux* fired her first trial shot at *Royal Sovereign*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] *Royal Sovereign* had all sails out and, having recently had her bottom cleaned, outran the rest of the British fleet.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] As she approached the allied line, she came under fire from *Fougueux*, *Indomptable*, *San Justo*, and *San Leandro*, before breaking the line just astern of Admiral Alava's flagship Spanish ship *Santa Ana*, into which she fired a devastating double-shotted raking broadside.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] For 40 minutes, *Victory* was under fire from *Héros*, *Santísima Trinidad*, *Redoutable*, and *Neptune*; although many shots went astray, others killed and wounded a number of her crew and shot her wheel away, so that she had to be steered from her tiller belowdecks, all before she could respond.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] This volley of gunfire from the *Victory* immediately knocked the French flagship out of action.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] *Victory* locked masts with the French *Redoutable,* whose crew, including a strong infantry corps (with three captains and four lieutenants), gathered for an attempt to board and seize *Victory*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] A musket bullet fired from the mizzentop of *Redoutable* struck Nelson in the left shoulder, passed through his spine at the sixth and seventh thoracic vertebrae, and lodged two inches below his right scapula in the muscles of his back.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson exclaimed, "They finally succeeded, I am dead." He was carried below decks.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] At 13:55, the French Captain Lucas of *Redoutable*, with 99 fit men out of 643 and severely wounded himself, surrendered.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The French *Bucentaure* was isolated by *Victory* and *Temeraire*, and then engaged by *Neptune*, *Leviathan*, and *Conqueror*; similarly, *Santísima Trinidad* was isolated and overwhelmed, surrendering after three hours.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] As more and more British ships entered the battle, the ships of the allied centre and rear were gradually overwhelmed.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The allied van, after long remaining quiescent, made a futile demonstration and then sailed away.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] During the combat, Gravina was wounded, while Dionisio Alcalá-Galiano and Cosme Damián Churruca – commanders of the *Bahama* and *San Juan Nepomuceno*, respectively – were killed after ordering their ships not to surrender.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Gravina died from his wounds months later.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The British took 20 vessels of the Franco-Spanish fleet and lost none.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Among the captured French ships were *Aigle*, *Algésiras*, *Berwick*, *Bucentaure*, *Fougueux*, *Intrépide*, *Redoutable*, and *Swiftsure*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The Spanish ships taken were *Argonauta*, *Bahama*, *Monarca*, *Neptuno*, *San Agustín*, *San Ildefonso*, *San Juan Nepomuceno*, *Santísima Trinidad*, and *Santa Ana*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Of these, *Redoutable* sank, and *Santísima Trinidad* and *Argonauta* were scuttled by the British.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] *Achille* exploded, *Intrépide* and *San Augustín* burned, and *Aigle*, *Berwick*, *Fougueux*, and *Monarca* were wrecked in a gale following the battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] As Nelson lay dying, he ordered the fleet to anchor, as a storm was predicted.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] However, when the storm blew up, many of the severely damaged ships sank or ran aground on the shoals.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] A few of them were recaptured, some by the French and Spanish prisoners overcoming the small prize crews, others by ships sallying from Cádiz.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Surgeon William Beatty heard Nelson murmur, "Thank God I have done my duty"; when he returned, Nelson's voice had faded, and his pulse was very weak.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] He looked up as Beatty took his pulse, then closed his eyes.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson died at half-past four, three hours after being hit.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Towards the end of the battle, and with the combined fleet being overwhelmed, the still relatively un-engaged portion of the van under Rear-Admiral Dumanoir Le Pelley tried to come to the assistance of the collapsing centre.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] After failing to fight his way through, he decided to break off the engagement, and led four French ships, his flagship the 80-gun *Formidable*, the 74-gun ships *Scipion*, *Duguay-Trouin* and *Mont Blanc* away from the fighting.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] He headed at first for the Straits of Gibraltar, intending to carry out Villeneuve's original orders and make for Toulon.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] On 22 October he changed his mind, remembering a powerful British squadron under Rear-Admiral Thomas Louis was patrolling the straits, and headed north, hoping to reach one of the French Atlantic ports.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] With a storm gathering in strength off the Spanish coast, he sailed westwards to clear Cape St.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Vincent, prior to heading north-west, swinging eastwards across the Bay of Biscay, and aiming to reach the French port at Rochefort.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] These four ships remained at large until their encounter with and attempt to chase a British frigate brought them in range of a British squadron under Sir Richard Strachan, which captured them all on 4 November 1805 at the Battle of Cape Ortegal.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Only eleven allied ships escaped to Cádiz, and, of those, only five were considered seaworthy.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The seriously wounded Admiral Gravina passed command of the remainder of the fleet over to Commodore Julien Cosmao on 23 October.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] From shore, the allied commanders could see an opportunity for a rescue mission.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Cosmao claimed in his report that the rescue plan was entirely his idea, but Vice-Admiral Escaño recorded a meeting of Spanish and French commodores at which a planned rescue was discussed and agreed upon.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Enrique MacDonnell and Cosmao were of equal rank and both raised commodore's pennants before hoisting anchor.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Both sets of mariners were determined to make an attempt to recapture some of the prizes.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Cosmao ordered the rigging of his ship, the 74-gun *Pluton*, to be repaired and reinforced her crew (which had been depleted by casualties from the battle), with sailors from the French frigate *Hermione*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Taking advantage of a favourable northwesterly wind, *Pluton*, the 80-gun *Neptune* and *Indomptable*, the Spanish 100-gun *Rayo* and 74-gun *San Francisco de Asis*, together with five French frigates and two brigs, sailed out of the harbour towards the British.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Soon after leaving port, the wind shifted to west-southwest, raising a heavy sea with the result that most of the British prizes broke their tow ropes, and drifting far to leeward, were only partially resecured.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The combined squadron came in sight at noon, causing Collingwood to summon his most battle-ready ships to meet the threat.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] In doing so, he ordered them to cast off towing their prizes.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] He had formed a defensive line of ten ships by three o'clock in the afternoon and approached the Franco-Spanish squadron, covering the remainder of their prizes which stood out to sea.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The Franco-Spanish squadron, numerically inferior, chose not to approach within gunshot and then declined to attack.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Collingwood also chose not to seek action, and in the confusion of the powerful storm, the French frigates managed to retake two Spanish ships of the line which had been cast off by their British captors, the 112-gun *Santa Ana* and 80-gun *Neptuno*, taking them in tow and making for Cádiz.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] On being taken in tow, the Spanish crews rose up against their British prize crews, putting them to work as prisoners.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Despite this initial success, the Franco-Spanish force, hampered by battle damage, struggled in the heavy seas.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] *Neptuno* was eventually wrecked off Rota in the gale, while *Santa Ana* reached port.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The French 80-gun ship *Indomptable* was wrecked on the 24th or 25th off the town of Rota on the northwest point of the bay of Cádiz.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] At the time *Indomptable* had 1,200 men on board, but no more than 100 were saved.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] *San Francisco de Asís* was driven ashore in Cádiz Bay, near Fort Santa Catalina, although her crew was saved.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] *Rayo*, an old three-deck vessel with more than 50 years of service, anchored off Sanlúcar, a few leagues to the northwest of Rota.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] There, she lost her masts, already damaged in the battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Heartened by the approach of the squadron, the French crew of the former flagship *Bucentaure* also rose up and retook the ship from the British prize crew but she was wrecked later on 23 October.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] *Aigle* escaped from the British ship HMS *Defiance*, but was wrecked off the Port of Santa María on 23 October; while the French prisoners on *Berwick* cut the tow cables, but caused her to founder off Sanlúcar on 22 October.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The crew of *Algésiras* rose up and managed to sail into Cádiz.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Observing that some of the leewardmost of the prizes were escaping towards the Spanish coast, *Leviathan* asked for and was granted permission by Collingwood to try to retrieve the prizes and bring them to anchor.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] *Leviathan* chased *Monarca*, but on 24 October she came across *Rayo*, dismasted but still flying Spanish colours, at anchor off the shoals of Sanlúcar.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] At this point the 74-gun HMS *Donegal*, en route from Gibraltar under Captain Pulteney Malcolm, was seen approaching from the south on the larboard tack with a moderate breeze from northwest-by-north and steered directly for the Spanish three-decker.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] At about ten o'clock, just as *Monarca* had got within little more than a mile of *Rayo*, *Leviathan* fired a warning shot wide of *Monarca*, to oblige her to drop anchor.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The shot fell between *Monarca* and *Rayo*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The latter, conceiving that it was probably intended for her, hauled down her colours, and was taken by HMS *Donegal*, who anchored alongside and took off the prisoners.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] *Leviathan* resumed her pursuit of *Monarca*, eventually catching up and forcing her to surrender.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] On boarding her, her British captors found that she was in a sinking state, and so removed the British prize crew, and nearly all of her original Spanish crew members.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The nearly empty *Monarca* parted her cable and was wrecked during the night.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Despite the efforts of her British prize crew, *Rayo* was driven onshore on 26 October and wrecked, with the loss of 25 men.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The remainder of the prize crew were made prisoners by the Spanish.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] On balance, the allied counter-attack achieved little.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] In forcing the British to suspend their repairs to defend themselves, it influenced Collingwood's decision to sink or set fire to the most damaged of his remaining prizes.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Cosmao retook two Spanish ships of the line, but it cost him one French and two Spanish vessels to do so.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Fearing their loss, the British burnt or sank *Santísima Trinidad*, *Argonauta*, *San Antonio*, and *Intrépide*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Only four of the British prizes, the French *Swiftsure* and the Spanish *Bahama*, *San Ildefonso* and *San Juan Nepomuceno* survived to be taken to Britain.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] After the end of the battle and storm only nine ships of the line were left in Cádiz.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Spanish military garrisons and civilians set out to rescue survivors from the numerous shipwrecks scattered along the Andalusian coast.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] British prize crews were captured and given good treatment.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] On 27 October, Collingwood offered the governor of Cádiz to put his Spanish wounded prisoners ashore and set them free.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The governor and Gravina offered in exchange to release their British prisoners, who boarded the British fleet.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The French later joined this humanitarian agreement.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The disparity in losses has been attributed by some historians less to Nelson's daring tactics than to the difference in fighting readiness of the two fleets.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson's fleet was made up of ships of the line which had spent a considerable amount of sea time during the months of blockades of French ports, whilst the French fleet had generally been at anchor in port.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] However, Villeneuve's fleet had just spent months at sea crossing the Atlantic twice, which supports the proposition that the main difference between the two fleets' combat effectiveness was the morale of the leaders.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The daring tactics employed by Nelson were to ensure a strategically decisive result.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The results vindicated his naval judgement.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] When Rosily arrived in Cádiz, he found only five French ships, rather than the 18 he was expecting.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The surviving ships remained bottled up in Cádiz until 1808 when Napoleon invaded Spain.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The French ships were then seized by the Spanish forces and put into service against France.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] HMS *Victory* made her way to Gibraltar for repairs, carrying Nelson's body.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] She put into Rosia Bay, Gibraltar and after emergency repairs were carried out, returned to Britain.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Many of the injured crew were taken ashore at Gibraltar and treated in the Naval Hospital.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Men who subsequently died from injuries sustained at the battle are buried in or near the Trafalgar Cemetery, at the south end of Main Street, Gibraltar.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] One Royal Marine officer, Captain Charles Adair, was killed on board *Victory*, and Royal Marine Lieutenant Lewis Buckle Reeve was seriously wounded and laid next to Nelson.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The battle took place the day after the Battle of Ulm, and Napoleon did not hear about it for weeks—the Grande Armée had left Boulogne to fight Britain's allies before they could combine their armies.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] He had tight control over the Paris media and kept the defeat a closely guarded secret for over a month, at which point newspapers proclaimed it to have been a tremendous victory.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] In a counter-propaganda move, a fabricated text declaring the battle a "spectacular victory" for the French and Spanish was published in *Herald* and attributed to *Le Moniteur Universel*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Vice-Admiral Villeneuve was taken prisoner aboard his flagship and taken back to Britain.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] After his parole in 1806, he returned to France, where he was found dead in his inn room during a stop on the way to Paris, with six stab wounds in the chest from a dining knife.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] It was officially recorded that he had committed suicide.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Despite the British victory over the Franco-Spanish navies, Trafalgar had negligible impact on the remainder of the War of the Third Coalition.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Less than two months later, Napoleon decisively defeated the Third Coalition at the Battle of Austerlitz, knocking Austria out of the war and forcing the dissolution of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Although Trafalgar meant France could no longer challenge Britain at sea, Napoleon proceeded to establish the Continental System in an attempt to deny Britain trade with the continent.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The Napoleonic Wars continued for another ten years after Trafalgar.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson's body was preserved in a barrel of brandy for the trip home to a grand state funeral.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Following the battle, the Royal Navy was never again seriously challenged by the French fleet in a large-scale engagement.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Napoleon had already abandoned his plans of invasion before the battle and they were never revived.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The battle did not mean, however, that the French naval challenge to Britain was over.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] First, as the French control over the continent expanded, Britain had to take active steps with the Battle of Copenhagen in 1807 and elsewhere in 1808 to prevent the ships of smaller European navies from falling into French hands.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] This effort was largely successful, but did not end the French threat as Napoleon instituted a large-scale shipbuilding programme that had produced a fleet of 80 ships of the line at the time of his fall from power in 1814, with more under construction.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] However, despite constituting a substantial fleet in being, these had no impact on Britain's naval superiority throughout the conflict.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] For almost 10 years after Trafalgar, the Royal Navy maintained a close blockade of French bases and observed the growth of the French fleet.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] In the end, Napoleon's Empire was destroyed by land before his ambitious naval build-up could be completed.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The Royal Navy dominance of the sea would not be meaningfully tested until the Battle of Jutland in World War One.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Although the victory at Trafalgar was typically given as the reason at the time, modern historical analyses suggest that relative economic strength was an important underlying cause of British naval mastery.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson became – and remains – Britain's greatest naval war hero, and an inspiration to the Royal Navy, yet his unorthodox tactics were seldom emulated by later generations.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The first monument to be erected in Britain to commemorate Nelson may be that raised on Glasgow Green in 1806, albeit possibly preceded by a monument at Taynuilt, near Oban in Scotland dated 1805, both also commemorating the many Scots crew and captains at the battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The 144-foot-tall (44 m) *Nelson Monument* on Glasgow Green was designed by David Hamilton and paid for by public subscription.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Around the base are the names of his major victories: Aboukir (1798), Copenhagen (1801) and Trafalgar (1805).
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The Nelson Monument overlooking Portsmouth was built in 1807–08 with money subscribed by sailors and marines who served at Trafalgar.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] In 1808, Nelson's Pillar was erected by leading members of the Anglo-Irish aristocracy in Dublin to commemorate Nelson and his achievements (between 10% and 20% of the sailors at Trafalgar had been from Ireland), and remained until it was destroyed in a bombing by "Old IRA" members in 1966.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson's Monument in Edinburgh was built between 1807 and 1815 in the form of an upturned telescope, and in 1853 a time ball was added which still drops at noon GMT to give a time signal to ships in Leith and the Firth of Forth.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] In summer this coincides with the *one o'clock gun* being fired.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] The Britannia Monument in Great Yarmouth was raised by 1819.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] Nelson's Column, Montreal began public subscriptions soon after news of the victory at Trafalgar arrived; the column was completed in the autumn of 1809 and still stands in Place Jacques Cartier.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] A statue of Lord Nelson stood in Bridgetown, Barbados, in what was also once known as Trafalgar Square, from 1813 to 2020.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] London's Trafalgar Square was named in honour of Nelson's victory.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p01] At the centre of the square there is the 45.1 m (148 ft) Nelson's Column, with a 5.5 m (18 ft) statue of Nelson on top.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] In 1905, there were events up and down the country to commemorate the centenary, although none were attended by any member of the Royal Family, apparently to avoid upsetting the French, with whom the United Kingdom had recently entered the *Entente Cordiale*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] King Edward VII did support the Nelson Centenary Memorial Fund of the British and Foreign Sailors Society, which sold Trafalgar centenary souvenirs marked with the royal cypher.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] A gala was held on 21 October at the Royal Albert Hall in aid of the fund, which included a specially commissioned film by Alfred John West entitled *Our Navy*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] The event ended with *God Save the King* and *La Marseillaise*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] The first performance of Sir Henry Wood's *Fantasia on British Sea Songs* occurred on the same day at a special Promenade Concert.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] In 2005 a series of events around the UK, part of the *Sea Britain* theme, marked the bicentenary of the Battle of Trafalgar.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] The 200th anniversary of the battle was also commemorated on six occasions in Portsmouth during June and July, at St Paul's Cathedral (where Nelson is entombed), in Trafalgar Square in London in October (*T Square 200*), and across the UK.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] On 28 June, Queen Elizabeth II was involved in the largest Fleet Review in modern times in the Solent, in which 167 ships from 35 nations took part.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] The Queen inspected the international fleet from the Antarctic patrol ship HMS *Endurance*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] The fleet included six aircraft carriers (modern capital ships): *Charles de Gaulle*, *Illustrious*, *Invincible*, *Ocean*, *Principe de Asturias* and *Saipan*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] In the evening a symbolic re-enactment of the battle was staged with fireworks and various small ships playing parts in the battle.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] On the actual anniversary day, 21 October, naval manoeuvres were conducted in Trafalgar Bay near Cádiz involving a combined fleet from Britain, Spain, and France.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battle-of-trafalgar-p02] Many descendants of people present at the battle, including members of Nelson's family, were at the ceremony.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battleground-video-game-series] Only 5,000 copies of the game were printed.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battleground-video-game-series] It received a score of 8/10 from CNET Gamecenter.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battleground-video-game-series] It was nominated for the 1998 Charles Roberts Award for "Best Pre-Twentieth Century Computer Wargame", which ultimately went to *The Great Battles Collector's Edition*.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battleground-video-game-series] In 1998, *Computer Gaming World* dubbed *Battleground* "the most successful wargame series".
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battleground-video-game-series] The three *Battleground* games of 1996—*Shiloh*, *Antietam* and *Waterloo*—collectively won *Computer Games Strategy Plus*'s wargame of the year award for that year.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battleground-video-game-series] The *Battleground* series, collectively, was named the 75th best computer game ever by *PC Gamer UK* in 1997.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/battleground-video-game-series] The editors called it "a fine expose of table top wargaming on the PC".
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/computer-games-magazine] The magazine's original editor-in-chief, Brian Walker, sold *Strategy Plus* to the United States retail chain Chips & Bits in 1991.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/computer-games-magazine] Based in Vermont and owned by Tina and Yale Brozen, Chips & Bits retitled *Strategy Plus* to *Computer Games Strategy Plus* after the purchase.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/computer-games-magazine] Its circulation rose to around 130,000 monthly copies by the mid-1990s.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/computer-games-magazine] By 1998, *Computer Games Strategy Plus* was the United States' third-largest computer game magazine, with a circulation of 184,299.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/computer-games-magazine] According to editor-in-chief Steve Bauman, this number rose to 220,000 in 1999.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/computer-games-magazine] Chips & Bits was purchased by theGlobe.com in January 2000, alongside *Computer Games Strategy Plus* and its publishing division, Strategy Plus, Inc.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/computer-games-magazine] By March 2000, *Computer Games*' circulation had reached 240,000 copies; roughly 300,000 units of each issue were printed per month.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/computer-games-magazine] It remained the United States' third-biggest computer game magazine by that date, according to Yale Brozen, and the publication's Ed Mitchell estimated that it was Vermont's largest magazine in any field.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/computer-games-magazine] Its official website, cdmag.com, averaged one million unique visits per month by early 2000.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/computer-games-magazine] The magazine experienced major growth during 2000: tracking firm BPA International recorded its average circulation from July–December as 374,576 copies, while the December issue rose to 450,515.
[src:age-of-sail-video-game/computer-games-magazine] *Computer Games Magazine* was subsequently redesigned, starting from its June 2001 issue.
